# Building Layouts with Flexbox

Now that you know the Flexbox properties, the skill is combining them to build the page layouts you see every day: navigation bars, card grids, sidebars, footers, and centred hero sections.

## Common Layout Patterns

### Pattern 1 — Horizontal Navigation Bar
```css
nav {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
}
```

### Pattern 2 — Equal-Width Card Row
```css
.cards { display: flex; gap: 16px; }
.card  { flex: 1; }
```

### Pattern 3 — Centred Content (vertical + horizontal)
```css
.hero {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  min-height: 400px;
}
```

### Pattern 4 — Sidebar + Main Content
```css
.layout  { display: flex; gap: 24px; }
.sidebar { width: 240px; flex-shrink: 0; }
.main    { flex: 1; }
```

### Pattern 5 — Wrapping Card Grid
```css
.grid {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 16px;
}
.grid-item {
  flex: 0 0 calc(33.333% - 11px); /* 3 columns with gap */
}
```

## flex-wrap for Responsive Rows

By default, flex items never wrap — they shrink to fit. Adding `flex-wrap: wrap` lets items drop to the next line when there is not enough space:

```css
.cards {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 16px;
}
.card { flex: 0 0 300px; }  /* minimum 300px each */
```

## Centering a Single Item

```css
.parent {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
}
```

This is the modern replacement for the old `margin: auto` hack. Two lines of CSS and a child is perfectly centred both ways.

## Order Property

```css
.item { order: 2; }  /* default is 0; higher = later in visual order */
```

You can reorder flex items visually without changing the HTML source order. Useful for responsive design — show sidebar below content on mobile.

